{"segment_id": "00061", "page_num": 61, "segment": "CHAPTER 3\n\nMEASURING AND CHANGING\n\nCULTURE\n\nI\n\nt is practically a truism in DevOps circles that culture is of huge\n\nimportance. However, culture is intangible; there exist many denitions\n\nand models of culture. Our challenge was to nd a model of culture that\n\nwas well-dened in the scientic literature, could be measured effectively,\n\nand would have predictive power in our domain. Not only did we achieve\n\nthese objectives, we also discovered that it is possible to inuence and\n\nimprove culture by implementing DevOps practices.\n\nMODELING AND MEASURING CULTURE\n\nere are many approaches to modeling culture in the literature. You can\n\nchoose to look at national culture--for example, what country one belongs\n\nto. You may also talk about what organizational cultural values are enacted\n\nthat inuence the way teams behave. And even within organizational\n\nculture, there are several ways to dene and model\n\n\"culture.\"\n\nOrganizational culture can exist at three levels in organizations: basic\n\nassumptions, values, and artifacts (Schein 1985). At the rst level, basic", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "and models of culture. Our challenge was to nd a model of culture that MODELING AND MEASURING CULTURE", "l2_summary": "t is practically a truism in DevOps circles that culture is of huge However, culture is intangible; there exist many denitions and models of culture. Our challenge was to nd a model of culture that improve culture by implementing DevOps practices. MODELING AND MEASURING CULTURE", "prev_page": {"page_num": 60, "segment_id": "00060"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 62, "segment_id": "00062"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": true, "key_terms": ["culture", "organizational", "measuring", "devops", "there", "exist", "many", "model", "literature", "also"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["DevOps practices"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["culture model effectiveness", "predictive power"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["measuring culture", "changing culture", "DevOps practices"], "key_concepts": ["intangible nature of culture", "modeling and measuring culture", "influence and improvement of culture"], "problem_statement": "Measuring and changing the intangible aspect of organizational culture in DevOps context", "solution_approach": "Developing a well-defined model of culture, measuring its effectiveness, and finding ways to influence it through DevOps practices", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00062", "page_num": 62, "segment": "assumptions are formed over time as members of a group or organization\n\nmake sense of relationships, events, and activities. ese interpretations\n\nare the least \"visible\" of the levels--and are the things that we just \"know,\"\n\nand may nd difficult to articulate, after we have been long enough in a\n\nteam.\n\ne second level of organizational culture are values, which are more\n\n\"visible\" to group members as these collective values and norms can be\n\ndiscussed and even debated by those who are aware of them. Values provide\n\na lens through which group members view and interpret the relationships,\n\nevents, and activities around them. Values also inuence group interactions\n\nand activities by establishing social norms, which shape the actions of\n\ngroup members and provide contextual rules (Bansal 2003). ese are quite\n\noften the \"culture\" we think of when we talk about the culture of a team\n\nand an organization.\n\ne third level of organizational culture is the most visible and can be\n\nobserved\n\nin artifacts. ese artifacts can\n\ninclude written mission\n\nstatements or creeds, technology, formal procedures, or even heroes and\n\nrituals (Pettigrew 1979).\n\nBased on discussions in DevOps circles and the importance of\n\n\"organizational culture\" at the second level, we decided to select a model\n\ndened by sociologist Ron Westrum. Westrum had been researching\n\nhuman factors in system safety, particularly in the context of accidents in\n\ntechnological domains that were highly complex and risky, such as aviation\n\nand healthcare. In 1988, he developed a typology of organizational cultures\n\n(Westrum 2014):\n\nPathological (power-oriented) organizations are characterized by\n\nlarge amounts of fear and threat. People often hoard information or", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used"