{"segment_id": "00096", "page_num": 96, "segment": "Figure 5.1: Deploys per Developer per Day\n\nAs the number of developers increases, we found:\n\nLow performers deploy with decreasing frequency.\n\nMedium performers deploy at a constant frequency.\n\nHigh performers deploy at a signicantly increasing frequency.\n\nBy focusing on the factors that predict high delivery performance--a\n\ngoal-oriented generative culture, a modular architecture, engineering\n\npractices that enable continuous delivery, and effective leadership--we can\n\nscale deployments per developer per day linearly or better with the", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "Figure 5.1: Deploys per Developer per Day Low performers deploy with decreasing frequency. Medium performers deploy at a constant frequency.", "l2_summary": "Figure 5.1: Deploys per Developer per Day Low performers deploy with decreasing frequency. Medium performers deploy at a constant frequency. High performers deploy at a signicantly increasing frequency. By focusing on the factors that predict high delivery performance--a scale deployments per developer per day linearly or better with the", "prev_page": {"page_num": 95, "segment_id": "00095"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 97, "segment_id": "00097"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["performers", "deploy", "frequency", "developer", "high", "delivery"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "devops|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["modular architecture"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["deploy frequency per developer"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["deploy frequency", "developer performance", "scaling deployments"], "key_concepts": ["low performers", "medium performers", "high performers", "continuous delivery"], "problem_statement": "Optimizing deployment frequency per developer", "solution_approach": "Focusing on goal-oriented generative culture, modular architecture, engineering practices for continuous delivery, and effective leadership", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00097", "page_num": 97, "segment": "number of developers. is allows our business to move faster as we add\n\nmore people, not slow down, as is more typically the case.\n\nALLOW TEAMS TO CHOOSE THEIR OWN\nTOOLS\n\nIn many organizations, engineers must use tools and frameworks from an\n\napproved list. is approach typically serves one or more of the following\n\npurposes:\n\nReducing the complexity of the environment\n\nEnsuring the necessary skills are in place to manage the\n\ntechnology throughout its lifecycle\n\nIncreasing purchasing power with vendors\n\nEnsuring all technologies are correctly licensed\n\nHowever, there is a downside to this lack of exibility: it prevents\n\nteams from choosing technologies that will be most suitable for their\n\nparticular needs, and from experimenting with new approaches and\n\nparadigms to solve their problems.\n\nOur analysis shows that tool choice is an important piece of technical\n\nwork. When teams can decide which tools they use, it contributes to\n\nsoftware delivery performance and,\n\nin\n\nturn,\n\nto organizational\n\nperformance. is isn't surprising. e technical professionals who\n\ndevelop and deliver software and run complex infrastructures make these\n\ntool choices based on what is best for completing their work and\n\nsupporting their users. Similar results have been found in other studies of", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "more people, not slow down, as is more typically the case. ALLOW TEAMS TO CHOOSE THEIR OWN\nTOOLS software delivery performance and,", "l2_summary": "more people, not slow down, as is more typically the case. ALLOW TEAM