{"segment_id": "00098", "page_num": 98, "segment": "technical professionals (e.g., Forsgren et al. 2016), suggesting that the\n\nupsides of delegating tool choice to teams may outweigh the\n\ndisadvantages.\n\nat said, there is a place for standardization, particularly around the\n\narchitecture and conguration of infrastructure. e benets of a\n\nstandardized operational platform are discussed at length by Humble\n\n(2017). Another example is Steve Yegge's description of Amazon's move to\n\nan SOA, in which he notes, \"Debugging problems with someone else's code\n\ngets a LOT harder, and is basically impossible unless there is a universal\n\nstandard way to run every service in a debuggable sandbox\" (Yegge 2011).\n\nAnother nding in our research is that teams that build security into\n\ntheir work also do better at continuous delivery. A key element of this is\n\nensuring that information security teams make preapproved, easy-toconsume libraries, packages, toolchains, and processes available for\n\ndevelopers and IT operations to use in their work.\n\nere is no contradiction here. When the tools provided actually make\n\nlife easier for the engineers who use them, they will adopt them of their\n\nown free will. is is a much better approach than forcing them to use\n\ntools that have been chosen for the convenience of other stakeholders. A\n\nfocus on usability and customer satisfaction is as important when\n\nchoosing or building tools for internal customers as it is when building\n\nproducts for external customers, and allowing your engineers to choose\n\nwhether or not to use them ensures that we keep ourselves honest in this\n\nrespect.\n\nARCHITECTS SHOULD FOCUS ON ENGINEERS\n\nAND OUTCOMES, NOT TOOLS OR", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Stev