{"segment_id": "00171", "page_num": 171, "segment": "In the next chapters, we discuss the steps we took to ensure the data we\n\ncollected from our surveys was good and reliable. en, we look into why\n\nsurveys may be a preferred source of data for measurement--both in a\n\nresearch project like ours and in your own systems.\n\n1 http:///spurious-correlations.\n\n2 Pearson correlations measure the strength of a linear relationship between two variables, called\nPearson's r. It is often referred to as just correlation and takes a value between -1 and 1. If two\n\nvariables have a perfect linear correlation, that is they move together exactly, r = 1. If they move in\nexactly opposite directions, r = -1. If they are not correlated at all, r = 0.", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "2 Pearson correlations measure the strength of a linear relationship between two variables, called\nPearson's r. variables have a perfect linear correlation, that is they move together exactly, r = 1. If they move in\nexactly opposite directions, r = -1.", "l2_summary": "collected from our surveys was good and reliable. surveys may be a preferred source of data for measurement--both in a 1 http:///spurious-correlations. 2 Pearson correlations measure the strength of a linear relationship between two variables, called\nPearson's r. variables have a perfect linear correlation, that is they move together exactly, r = 1. If they move in\nexactly opposite directions, r = -1.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 170, "segment_id": "00170"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 172, "segment_id": "00172"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code":