{"segment_id": "00259", "page_num": 259, "segment": "midst of a storm, to a hard pivot in my PhD program, then inviting myself\n\ninto the State of DevOps Reports, and now nally this book. Your support,\n\nencouragement, and wisdom--in life and in tech--have been invaluable.\n\nSuzie! How did I ever get so lucky? I had an advisor who took a gamble\n\non a PhD student who promised you that studying tech professionals,\n\ntheir tools, and their environment--and how it all impacted their work--\n\nwould be important and relevant. (ose at top PhD programs will\n\nunderstand that this is, indeed, a gamble, with real risks involved.) Ten\n\nyears later, my research has grown and evolved and we call it DevOps.\n\nMany thanks to you, Suzanne Weisband, for trusting my instincts and\n\nguiding my research those early years. You've been the best advisor,\n\ncheerleader, and now friend.\n\nTo my post-doc advisors, mentors, and frequent peer-review coauthors\n\nAlexandra Durcikova and Rajiv Sabherwal: you also took risks conducting\n\nresearch with me in a new context, and I have learned so much from our\n\ncollaborations. My methods are stronger, my arguments more reasoned,\n\nand my ability to see a problem space is more developed. ank you.\n\nMany thanks to the DevOps community, who welcomed and accepted a\n\ncrazy researcher and have participated in the studies and shared your\n\nstories. My work is better because of you, and more importantly, I am\n\nbetter because of you. Much love.\n\nAnd nally, thanks to Diet Coke for getting me through long stints of\n\nwriting and editing.\n\nJEZ", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "I had an advisor who took a gamble Many thanks to the DevOps community, who welcomed and accepted a My work is better because of you, and more importantly, I am", "l2_summary": "into the State of DevOps Reports, and now nally this book. I had an advisor who took a gamble on a PhD student who promised you that studying tech professionals, Many thanks to the DevOps community, who welcomed and accepted a My work is better because of you, and more importantly, I am better because of you.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 258, "segment_id": "00258"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 260, "segment_id": "00260"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["devops", "have", "research", "thanks", "more", "nally", "tech", "advisor", "took", "gamble"], "content_type": "review", "domain": "devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Suzanne Weisband", "Alexandra Durcikova", "Rajiv Sabherwal"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["DevOps research", "PhD program experience", "academic support"], "key_concepts": ["support and encouragement", "research evolution", "DevOps methodology"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00260", "page_num": 260, "segment": "Many thanks to my wife and BFF Rani for supporting me working on this\n\nbook even after I promised I wouldn't write another one. You're the best! I\n\nlove you. anks to my daughters for bringing so much fun and joy into\n\nthe proceedings, and to my mum and dad for supporting my adventures\n\nwith computers as a kid.\n\nNicole took an industry survey, Puppet's State of DevOps Report, and\n\nturned it into a scientic tool. Our industry has always struggled with\n\napplying science to the development and operation of software products\n\nand services. e social systems that support software delivery are too\n\nirreducibly complex to make randomized, controlled experiments\n\npractical. In retrospect, the solution was clear: use behavioral science to\n\nstudy these systems. Nicole's careful, thorough pioneering of this\n\napproach has produced incredible results, and it's hard to overstate the\n\nimpact of her work. It's been an honor to be her partner in this research,\n\nand I've learned an enormous amount. ank you.\n\ne reason I'm involved with this project at all is Gene, who invited me\n\nto be part of the State of DevOps team back in 2012. Gene, your passion\n\nfor this project--and, on a personal level, for challenging my hypotheses\n\nand analysis (yes, I'm talking about trunk-based development)--has made\n\nthis both substantially more rigorous and highly rewarding.\n\nI also want to thank the Puppet team who've contributed so much to\n\nthis work and without whom it wouldn't exist, particularly Alanna Brown,\n\nNigel Kersten, and Aliza Earnshaw. ank you.\n\nGENE", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "Nicole took an industry survey, Puppet's State of DevOps Report, and Our industry has always struggled with to be part of the State of DevOps team back in 2012.", "l2_summary": "Nicole took an industry survey, Puppet's State of DevOps Report, and Our industry has always struggled with applying science to the development and operation of software products e reason I'm involved with this project at all is Gene, who invited me to be part of the State of DevOps team back in 2012. I also want to thank the Puppet team who've contributed so much to", "prev_page": {"page_num": 259, "segment_id": "00259"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 261, "segment_id": "00261"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["gene", "supporting", "wouldn", "much", "nicole", "industry", "puppet", "state", "devops", "science"], "content_type": "review", "domain": "devops|data_science", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Puppet"], "people": ["Nicole", "Gene", "Rani", "Alanna Brown", "Nigel Kersten", "Aliza Earnshaw"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Puppet's State of DevOps Report"], "topics": ["DevOps research", "behavioral science in DevOps", "support from family and colleagues"], "key_concepts": ["behavioral science in DevOps", "impact of Nicole's work", "Gene's contribution"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00261", "page_num": 261, "segment": "I am grateful to Margueritte, my loving wife of twelve years, as well as my\n\nsons, Reid, Parker, and Grant--I know that I could not do the work I love\n\nwithout their support and tolerance of deadlines, late nights, and roundthe-clock texting. And of course, my parents, Ben and Gail Kim, for\n\nhelping me become a nerd early in life.\n\nis research with Jez and Nicole has been some of the most satisfying\n\nand illuminating I've ever had the privilege of working on--no one could\n\nask for a better team of collaborators. I genuinely believe this work\n\nsignicantly advances our profession, by helping us better dene how we\n\nimprove technology work, through rigorous theory building and testing.\n\nAnd of course, thank you to Alanna Brown and Nigel Kersten at Puppet\n\nfor the amazing 5+ year collaboration on State of DevOps project, from\n\nwhich so much of this book is based upon.", "source_file": "Forsgren N., Humble J., Kim G.- Accelerate. The Science of DevOps - 2018.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "16", "chapter_title": "Copyright (c) 2018 by Karen Whitley Bell and Steve Bell,", "section_num": "16.2", "section_title": "ING's New Agile Organizational Model Has No Fixed Structure--It", "l1_summary": "sons, Reid, Parker, and Grant--I know that I could not do the work I love And of course, my parents, Ben and Gail Kim, for I genuinely believe this work", "l2_summary": "sons, Reid, Parker, and Grant--I know that I could not do the work I love And of course, my parents, Ben and Gail Kim, for helping me become a nerd early in life. ask for a better team of collaborators. I genuinely believe this work signicantly advances our profession, by helping us better dene how we", "prev_page": {"page_num": 260, "segment_id": "00260"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 262, "segment_id": "00262"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram